    <exercise label="Library__Michigan__Chap16Sec5__Q03__pg" xml:id="ex-11-8-WW-paraboloid-spherical">
    <!--<title>Find an equation of a paraboloid in spherical coordinates</title>-->
        <webwork source="Library/Michigan/Chap16Sec5/Q03.pg"/>
    </exercise>

    

    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Consider the solid region <m>S</m> bounded above by the paraboloid <m>z = 16 - x^2 - y^2</m> and below by the paraboloid <m>z = 3x^2 + 3y^2</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Describe parametrically the curve in <m>\R^3</m> in which these two surfaces intersect.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <m>x(t) = 2\cos(t)</m>,
            <m>y(t) = 2\sin(t)</m>, and <m>z=12</m> for <m>0 \leq t \leq 2\pi</m>
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Setting <m>16-x^2-y^2</m> equal to <m>3x^2+3y^2</m> yields the equation <m>x^2+y^2=4</m>. When <m>x^2+y^2=4</m>, we have <m>z = 12</m>. This is the circle centered at <m>(0,0,12)</m> with radius 2 in the <m>z=12</m> plane, and has the parameterization <m>x(t) = 2\cos(t)</m>, <m>y(t) = 2\sin(t)</m>, and <m>z=12</m> for <m>0 \leq t \leq 2\pi</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In terms of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, write an equation to describe the projection of the curve onto the <m>xy</m>-plane.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The projection of this intersection curve onto the <m>x</m>-<m>y</m> plane is the circle centered at the origin of radius 2 and has parameterization <m>x(t) = 2\cos(t)</m> and <m>y(t) = 2\sin(t)</m> for <m>0 \leq t \leq 2\pi</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                What coordinate system do you think is most natural for setting up inequalities to describe the volume of the solid?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                Cylindrical
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                With the projection as a circle and the surfaces defined in terms of <m>x^2+y^2</m>, cylindrical coordinates seem a natural choice.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Set up a set of inequalities in whichever coordinate system you choose that will describe the solid volume <m>S</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <m>0 \geq z \geq 2\pi , \quad 0 \geq z \geq 2 , \quad 3r^2 \geq \theta \geq 16-r^2</m>
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <m>0 \geq z \geq 2\pi , \quad 0 \geq z \geq 2 , \quad 3r^2 \geq \theta \geq 16-r^2</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Try to draw a plot of the solid volume <m>S</m> by hand.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    </exercise>

   

